\i0  to be the leader of men because it short-circuited the male competitive drive.\
The meeting continued. She mostly listened. She did step in once when she sensed the beginning of a feeding frenzy around Ned. She didn\'92t like when people ganged up on each other. It was bad for business and rarely accomplished anything.  There was a hint of savage when it happened, and she had a strong dislike of anything savage.\
In some ways handling the problem was easy because there were many constraints.  Obeying the law, for example. They didn\'92t have a choice. They needed to appear as cooperative as possible, so no document-shredding, no email-deleting. The best approach was always, \'93We\'92re sorry, we made a mistake, we\'92re going to do our best to make it better.\'94\
The solution was simple: they were going to spend lots of money making things better. Lots of money. Not enough to bankrupt the company, but enough to hurt.  The bonuses were going to be small this year, and everyone in the room knew that. There was an undercurrent of sadness and loss in the room.\
Her mentor, the previous CEO, had said to her, \'93Remember: when you have a problem, and it can be fixed with money, you don\'92t have a problem \'97 you have an expense.\'94 Right now she had an expense. A very big expense.\
The purpose of the meeting had been to achieve consensus, and consensus had been achieved.\
The meeting adjourned. She asked, \'93Ned, could you please stay?\'94\
Everyone else in the room had left. Ned began stammering, saying that something about waivers being signed.\
She waved her hand, \'93Let\'92s not worry about the waivers for a minute. I have a few questions about what happened.\'94\
